    "summary": "The Karnak temple complex at ancient Thebes, modern Luxor in Upper Egypt, is the largest religious monument ever constructed, covering approximately 200 hectares and including multiple temples, chapels, pylons, and obelisks dedicated primarily to the god Amun-Ra. Although construction at the site began in the Middle Kingdom period around 2000 BC, Karnak reached its greatest extent and grandeur during the [[event:60|New Kingdom Egypt]], particularly through the extensive building programs of Thutmose I, [[event:1801|Hatshepsut]], [[event:1802|Thutmose III]], and [[event:1807|Ramesses II]], spanning roughly 1550–1100 BC.\n\nThe core of the complex is the Precinct of Amun-Ra, containing the Great Hypostyle Hall, one of the most awe-inspiring architectural achievements of the ancient world. The hypostyle hall covers approximately 5,000 square meters and contains 134 massive sandstone columns arranged in sixteen rows, with the central twelve columns rising to 21 meters in height and bearing open papyrus capitals. The columns and walls were originally brightly painted with scenes of royal ritual and divine encounter. The sheer scale of the hall conveys the overwhelming power and wealth concentrated at Thebes during the New Kingdom period.\n\nKarnak also served as an important political institution. The temples were not merely places of worship but economic centers controlling vast land holdings, workshops, and storehouses, and the priesthood of Amun that administered them became one of the most powerful institutions in Egypt. The complex was continuously modified and expanded by pharaohs who sought to associate themselves with Amun's authority, making it a palimpsest of New Kingdom royal ideology. Karnak remains one of Egypt's most visited archaeological sites and continues to yield important finds from ongoing excavations.",
